04563nam a2200613Ia 9780231559898DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315598987 a10.7312/case213442doi  a(DE-B1597)679655  a(OCoLC)1420168099  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB105.P535bC37 2024 7aPHI0180002bisacsh04a113/.8223/eng/202308111 aCasey, Edward S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlants in Place :bA Phenomenology of the Vegetal /cMichael Marder, Edward S. Casey. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b8 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Life Studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface: Walking Among Plants -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 The Placial Basis of Plant Sessility and Mobility -- t2 Peripheral Power: Structural Dynamics at the Edges of Plants -- tInterlude 1 How Plants Think -- t3. Taking Trees Over the Edge -- tInterlude 2 Plants Up- Close: The Case of Moss -- t4 The Shared Sociality of Trees, with Implications for Place -- tInterlude 3 Plants from Afar: As Seen in Landscape Painting -- t5 Attachment and Detachment in the Place of Plants -- tConclusion: The Fate of Places, the Fate of Plants -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPlants are commonly considered immobile, in contrast to humans and other animals. But vegetal existence involves many place-based forms of change: stems growing upward, roots spreading outward, fronds unfurling in response to sunlight, seeds traveling across wide distances, and other intricate relationships with the surrounding world. How do plants as sessile, growing, decaying, and metamorphosing beings shape the places they inhabit, and how are they shaped by them? How do human places interact with those of plants—in lived experience; in landscape painting; in cultivation and contemplation; in forests, fields, gardens, and cities?Examining these questions and many more, Plants in Place is a collaborative study of vegetal phenomenology at the intersection of Edward S. Casey’s phenomenology of place and Michael Marder’s plant-thinking. It focuses on both the microlevel of the dynamic constitution of plant edges or a child’s engagement with moss and the macrolevel of habitats that include the sociality of trees. This compelling portrait of plants and their places provides readers with new ways to appreciate the complexity and vitality of vegetal life. Eloquent, descriptively rich, and insightful, the book also shows how the worlds of plants can enhance our understanding and experience of place more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPlants (Philosophy)2DLC. 0aPlants (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aMarder, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishz978311131922308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023z9783111318646oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/case2134440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231559898423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231559898/original  a978-3-11-131922-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZDB-23-DPHb2023